1. Description of the Plan
The Celanese Americas Retirement Pension Plan (the "Plan") is a defined benefit pension plan sponsored by Celanese Americas
LLC (the "Company"), an indirect, wholly owned subsidiary of Celanese Corporation. The Plan covers certain employees of the
Company and its U.S. subsidiaries ("Participants"). The Plan is subject to the provisions of the Employee Retirement Income
Security Act of 1974, as amended ("ERISA"). Participants in the Plan should refer to the Plan document for more complete
details of the Plan's provisions.
Non-Union employees hired before January 1, 2001, with five or more years of service, as defined, are entitled to annual
pension benefits beginning at normal retirement age (65) equal to the greater of (a) 1.33% of the employee's final average
earnings multiplied by the employee's years of credited service, or (b) 1.67% of the employee's final average earnings
multiplied by the employee's years of credited service minus 50% of the employee's Social Security benefit multiplied by a
fraction, the numerator of which is the employee's years of credited service (to a maximum of 35 years) and the denominator of
which is 35. The Plan permits early retirement between ages 55 to 64. A Participant would be entitled to an unreduced early
retirement benefit if they are at least age 55 and stop working when the sum of their age and years of vesting service or credited
service (whichever is greater) equals at least 85 or they are at least age 60 and have at least 15 years of vesting or credited
service when they stop working. Otherwise, a Participant is entitled to an early retirement benefit reduced 4% by each year that
early retirement precedes the date the employee would be eligible for unreduced early retirement benefits. Employees may elect
to receive their pension benefits in the form of a joint and survivor annuity or a life annuity or certain and continuous annuity.
Employees who terminate before becoming vested forfeit their benefits. Forfeitures are fully retained by the Plan and are used
to reduce the Company's contributions to the Plan. If a married employee dies after being fully vested in the Plan, a death
benefit will be payable to the surviving spouse.
In 2001, the Plan began providing benefits for new employees, as defined by the Plan, hired after December 31, 2000 based
upon a different benefit formula ("Cash Balance Plan"). The Cash Balance Plan provides that for each Plan year an employee
works, as defined, the Company credits 5% of the employee's annual pensionable earnings, as defined, to a hypothetical Plan
account that has been established for each employee, and credits that account with interest. For a given year, the Plan's interest
rate is the annual rate of interest on 30-year Treasury securities as of August of the year prior to the first day of the Plan year.
The Plan's interest rate was 4.28% and 3.13% for the years ended December 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, respectively. An
employee's account balance grows with annual pay credits while employed and annual interest credits. Employees are vested
after completing three years of employment with the Company, as defined. If employees are vested when they leave the
Company, they have the option to take their account balance with them, either in a lump-sum payment or as an annuity. Once
vested, survivor benefits are applicable to married participants. Employees also have the choice to leave their account balance
in the Plan until the normal retirement age of 65.
Hourly (union and non-union) employees at select facilities, with five or more years of service, are entitled to 'dollar per month'
type pension benefits ("Flat Rate Plan"), credited through the date of termination and payable beginning at the normal
retirement age of 65. The monthly amounts range from $37 to $51 per month, depending on the employee's termination date.
Effective May 1, 2011, all union employees hired after April 30, 2011 are not eligible for the Flat Rate Plan. However, they are
eligible to participate in the Cash Balance Plan described above.
During 2013 and 2014, the Plan was amended and benefits offered to all union and non-union Participants were frozen, and the
Plan was closed to new participants. Accumulated benefits earned and service rendered under the Plan provisions for all
Participants will continue to be considered for purposes of determining retirement benefits and eligibility for early retirement.
In February 2021, the Plan sponsor received written notification from the Department of Labor (the "DOL") that the DOL
would be conducting an investigation of the Plan. The DOL concluded its investigation of the Plan in September 2024. No
violations of ERISA were asserted.
The Company's Benefits Committee ("Plan Administrator") oversees the administration of the Plan, and the Plan's Investment
Committee ("Investment Committee") has the discretionary authority to appoint agents to direct the purchase and sale of
investments in the Plan. The Company's sole member has appointed the Plan Administrator and the Investment Committee as
the named fiduciaries of the Plan.

2. Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
Basis of Accounting
The accompanying financial statements have been prepared in accordance with the accounting principles generally accepted in
the United States of America ("U.S. GAAP") for all periods presented.
Trust Agreement
The Company has a trust agreement with State Street Bank and Trust Company ("Trustee"). The agreement with the Trustee
establishes a qualified trust ("Trust") for the Plan.
Fair Value Measurements
The equity and debt securities objectives are to provide diversified exposure across the U.S. and global equity and fixed income
markets, and to manage the risks and returns of the Plan through the use of a fund of fund manager, comprised of multiple
managers and strategies. The fixed income strategy is designed to reduce liability-related interest rate risk by investing in bonds
that match the duration of the Plan liabilities. Derivatives-based strategies may be used to improve the effectiveness of the
hedges.
The Company determines fair value based on the price that would be received from selling an asset or paid to transfer a liability
in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. When determining the fair value measurements
for assets and liabilities required to be recorded at fair value, the Company considers assumptions that market participants
would use when pricing the asset or liability. Market participant assumptions are categorized by a three-tiered fair value
hierarchy which prioritizes the inputs used to measure fair value. The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted
prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs
(Level 3 measurement). This hierarchy requires entities to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of
unobservable inputs. If a financial instrument uses inputs that fall in different levels of the hierarchy, the instrument will be
categorized based upon the lowest level of input that is significant to the fair value calculation. Valuations for fund investments
such as common/collective trusts, registered investment companies and short-term investment funds, which do not have readily
determinable fair values, are typically estimated using a net asset value ("NAV") provided by a third party as a practical
expedient.
The levels of inputs used to measure fair value are as follows:
Level 1 - unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets or liabilities in active markets accessible by the Company
Level 2 - inputs that are observable in the marketplace other than those inputs classified as Level 1
Level 3 - inputs that are unobservable in the marketplace and significant to the valuation
Investment Valuation and Income Recognition
The assets of the Trust are primarily comprised of investments in equity and fixed income securities and are managed by
various investment managers appointed by the Investment Committee. Investments are stated at quoted market prices or
estimated fair value. Purchases and sales of securities are recorded on a trade-date basis. Interest income is recorded on an
accrual basis. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date. The Trustee uses a third party pricing vendor to provide quoted
market values for the Plan's individual marketable securities held by the Trust. Certain Plan investments participate in
commingled or pooled funds. Accordingly, the Trustee uses valuations provided by the investment manager/general partner of
such funds and reports these at estimated fair values.
Financial Instruments
In accordance with the investing strategy of the Plan's managed accounts, the Plan's investment managers may execute
transactions in various financial instruments that could give rise to varying degrees of off-balance sheet market and credit risk.
These instruments can be settled on an exchange or negotiated in the over-the-counter market. These financial instruments
primarily include swaps, options, forwards and futures contracts.
Market risk arises from the potential changes in value of financial instruments resulting from fluctuations in interest rates and
foreign exchange rates and in prices of debt and equity securities. The gross notional (or contractual) amounts used to express

through a variety of control procedures, including daily review of trading positions.
Actuarial Present Value of Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits represent the actuarially determined value of pension benefits that have been earned by Participants,
based on each Participant's pensionable earnings, service and age as of the valuation date. Accumulated plan benefits include
benefits expected to be paid to (a) retired or terminated employees or their beneficiaries, (b) beneficiaries of retired employees
who have died and (c) present employees or their beneficiaries. The benefits for active employees are based upon the pension
benefit calculations as outlined in the Plan document as of the date on which the benefit information is presented (the valuation
date). Benefits payable under all circumstances (e.g. retirement, death, disability and termination of employment) are included
to the extent they are deemed attributable to employee service rendered through the valuation date.
The actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits is the amount resulting from applying actuarial assumptions to adjust
the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time value of money (through discounts for interest) and the probability of payment
(by means of decrements such as for death, disability, termination or retirement) between the valuation date and the expected
date of payment. The actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits was prepared by an independent actuary as of
January 1, 2024. Had the valuation been performed as of December 31, 2023, there would be no material differences.

Valuation date First day of plan year.

during the plan year as required by regulations under IRC §430.
Decrement Timing The approach used is called rounded middle of year (rounded MOY)
decrement timing. Most events are assumed to occur at the middle of
year during which the eligibility condition will be met or the start/end
date will occur. For death and disability decrements, the rate applied
is based on the participant’s rounded age (nearest integer age) at the
beginning of the year, to align with the methodology generally used
to create those rate tables. For retirement and withdrawal
decrements: the age is generally the participant’s rounded age at the
middle of the year.
